The paper deals with the nonexistence of projective planes of order ten with weight 16 codewords, which is a problem in combinatorial design theory (DM). The use of Boolean satisfiability (SAT) and computer algebra system Maple suggests a focus on information theory (IT) and computational complexity (CC). The cube-and-conquer SAT solving paradigm and symmetry breaking techniques are commonly used in algorithms and data structures (DS) research. Finally, the use of nonisomorphic cases to check and the production of nonexistence proofs suggest a focus on logic in computer science (LO).
